<subsection xml:id="subsec-area-of-regular-and-irregular-polygons">
    <title>Area of regular and irregular polygons</title>
    <introduction>
        <definition xml:id="def-area-of-polygons">
            <statement>
               <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Polygon}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    A polygon is a closed 2D shape made up of 
                    straight lines. Examples include <m>\textbf{triangles, quadrilaterals, pentagons}</m> and <m>\textbf{hexagons.}</m> 
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Regular Polygons}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    
                    A polygon is regular if:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                All sides are equal in length.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                All interior angles are equal. eg equilateral triangle, square, regular pentagon, regular hexagon

                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>\textbf{Irregular Polygons}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    A polygon is irregular if:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Sides are not all the same length, and/or
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Angles are not all equal.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>
       
        </introduction>
        
