        <p>
            <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            A regular hexagon can always be split into 6 equal triangles called <m>\textbf{equilateral triangle.}</m>

        </p>
        <p>
            A regular hexagon has equal sides and angles. Its area can be found using the formula:
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>\text{Area}=\frac{1}{2} \times \text{Perimeter(P)} \times \text{apothem(a)}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Where <m>\text{Perimeter} = \text{Length} \times 6</m> and <m>\textbf{Apothem}</m> is the distance from the center of a regular hexagon to a side.
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>\textbf{Or}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            If you know apothem and side, use the formular below.
        </p>
        <p>
            <m>\text{Area} = \frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2} \times \text{s}^2</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            Where <m>\text{s}</m> is the length of one side of the hexagon.
        </p>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A regular hexagon has a side length of <m>4\, \text{cm}</m> as shown below. Find its area
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="hexagon3">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \draw (0:2) -- (60:2) -- (120:2) -- (180:2) -- (240:2) -- (300:2) -- cycle;
                        \filldraw  (0,0) circle (2pt) ;
                        \foreach \angle in {60,120}
                            \draw (0,0) -- (\angle:2);
                        \node at (0,2) {4 cm};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>

                </image>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The side length of the hexagon is <m>4 \, \text{cm}</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \text{Area} =\amp \frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2} \times \text{s}^2</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2} \times 4^2</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2} \times 16</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp 24\sqrt{3} \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                        <mrow>â \amp 41.57c\text{m}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore, the area of the hexagon is approximately <m>{\color{blue}41.57 \, \text{cm}^2}</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Bees build honeycombs using hexagonal cells. If each cell has a side 
                    length of <m>7.5 \, \text{km}</m>, what is the area of one cell?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    The side length of the hexagonal cell is <m>7.5 \, \text{km}</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \text{Area} =\amp \frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2} \times \text{s}^2</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2} \times (7.5)^2</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2} \times 56.25</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp 84.375\sqrt{3} \, \text{km}^2</mrow>
                        <mrow>â \amp 146.41\, \text{km}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    This implies that, the area of one hexagonal cell is approximately <m>{\color{blue}146.41 \, \text{km}^2}</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
