                            <p>
                                <md>
                                    <mrow> \text{Area} =\amp \frac{1}{2} \times \text{Perimeter} \times  \text{apothem}</mrow>
                                    <mrow> =\amp \frac{1}{2} \times 96 \times 30</mrow>
                                    <mrow> =\amp 48 \times 30</mrow>
                                    <mrow> =\amp 1440 \, \text{m}^2</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                            <p>
                                This implies that, the area of the hexagon is <m>{\color{blue}1440 \, \text{m}^2}</m>.
                            </p>

                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A regular hexagon has an area of <m>54\sqrt{3}\, \text{cm}^2</m>
                    . What is its side length?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>
                    To find the side length of a regular hexagon given its area, we can use the formula:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \text{Area} =\amp \frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2} \times \text{s}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Given that the area is <m>54\sqrt{3}\, \text{cm}^2</m>, we can set up the equation:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> 54\sqrt{3} =\amp \frac{3\sqrt{3}}{2} \times \text{s}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    To solve for <m>\text{s}</m>, we can rearrange the equation:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> \text{s}^2 =\amp \frac{54\sqrt{3} \times 2}{3\sqrt{3}}</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp \frac{108}{3}</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp 36</mrow>
                        <mrow> \text{s} =\amp \sqrt{36}</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp 6 \, \text{cm}</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Therefore, the side length of the regular hexagon is <m>{\color{blue}6 \, \text{cm}}</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        
    </subsubsection>
   
